{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480757"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:50:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:50:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"104"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/104"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.03,0.03,0.14,0.64]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109033"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/104"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91399"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109033"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three hours of right upper quadrant pain. The pain was constant in nature and has now settled. He has never had pain like this before. He has a medical history of a myocardial infarction five years ago. His medications include aspirin and atenolol. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 84/min, blood pressure 134/86 mmHg and temperature 37.2C. On abdominal examination, his abdomen is soft with no localising signs. An abdominal ultrasound examination shows a normal-looking gallbladder and no gallstones. It does show a 4.8cm diameter infra-renal aortic aneurysm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management for his abdominal aortic aneurysm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computer tomography angiography","Magnetic resonance angiography","No further investigation or treatment is required","Plan for endovascular repair","Repeat ultrasound examination in twelve months"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient had a presumed episode of biliary colic, but that has been excluded on the ultrasound. However, this investigation has identified an abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) which is almost certainly an incidental finding. Symptomatic AAA can present with abdominal or chest pain radiating to the back and can be associated with nausea, vomiting and syncope.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough there is variation in the international guidelines for the surveillance of asymptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysms (AAAs), the 2024 European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) guidelines are most widely followed, including in Australia and New Zealand. The ESVS guidelines recommend the following monitoring schedule for asymptomatic patients according to AAA diameter:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E25 - 29 mm: ultrasound every five years\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E30 - 39 mm: ultrasound every three years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E40 - 49 mm (men) or 40 \u2013 44 mm (women): annual ultrasound\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226550 mm (men) or \u226545 mm (women): ultrasound every six months.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226555 mm (men) or \u226550 mm (women): most surgeons would consider offering surgical repair; note that the threshold for elective repair in women is lower due to higher rupture risk at smaller diameters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that these are general guidelines, and different monitoring protocols may be utilised for patients with AAAs based on clinician judgement and patient factors (e.g. life expectancy, suitability for future repair, patient preferences).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further investigations or treatment required\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate, as a AAA with a diameter between 4 - 4.9 cm has a rupture risk of 1%, and if this progresses further to a diameter of 5 - 5.9 cm, the risk of rupture would further increase up to 10% each year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe benefit of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eelective aneurysm repair\u003C/strong\u003E is weighed with the risk of rupture. Indications to plan for endovascular repair include: 1. Size \u0026gt; 55mm; 2. Growth in size \u0026gt;1cm/year; 3. Symptomatic AAA; none of which are present in the current case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance angiography (MRA) \u003C/strong\u003Ehas limited utility in AAA and has been replaced by\u003Cstrong\u003E computer tomography angiography (CTA) \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich is considered the gold standard in assessing the diameter of AAA. However, this form of imaging is predominantly used for preoperative planning, and ultrasound is a sufficient method of imaging for surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Key decisions on the place of surgery in the management of an asymptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysm must be influenced by the diameter of the aneurysm.","Surveillance intervals for abdominal aortic aneurysms are determined by aneurysm size, with more frequent monitoring as size increases."],"references":["ESVS 2024 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm. In: European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://esvs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/ESVS-2024-AAA-Guidelines.pdf","Theivendran M, Chuen J. Updates on AAA screening and surveillance. Aust J Gen Pract. 2018 May;47(5):259-263. doi: 10.31128/AFP-07-17-4278. PMID: 29779301. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29779301/","Svensj\u00f6 S, Bj\u00f6rck M, Wanhainen A. Update on screening for abdominal aortic aneurysm: a topical review. Eur J Vasc Endovasc Surg. 2014 Dec;48(6):659-67. doi: 10.1016/j.ejvs.2014.08.029. Epub 2014 Nov 7. PMID: 25443524. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25443524/","Schanzer A, Oderich GS. Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms. N Engl J Med. 2021 Oct 28;385(18):1690-1698. doi: 10.1056/NEJMcp2108504. PMID: 34706173. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34706173/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91399"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"104"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91399"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:02:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:03:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"104"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109033"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes